ons_list against the heartbeat state from 13:36 UTC.\\n\\n**Last known state (13:36 UTC):**\\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` (5p QLHV) — running ✅\\n- `cron:6f3323ef` (5p DTLX) — running ✅\\n- `cron:e7885813` (Agent Status to Lead) — running ✅\\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` — done (since 13:00 UTC) ✅\\n\\n\\n- `telegram:group:-5168104492` — done (since 10:55 UTC) ✅\\n- `telegram:direct:6053576134` — done (since 13:15 UTC) ✅\\n- `main` — done (since 13:06 UTC) ✅\\n- `cron:b653a6c0` — zombie (stale) ✅\\n- `cron:ac986a8d` — zombie (stale) ✅\\n\\n**Current state (13:54 UTC):**\\n\\nLooking at the current session list, I'm seeing the main cron job is running and updated just now, while the 5p QLHV and 5p DTLX crons are both still active but haven't been updated in the last few minutes. There's also an active Telegram group session for the QLHV ecosystem that's been running for about two hours, and the DTLX ecosystem group is showing as done, which seems to be a recent change.\\n\\nI'm also noticing some stale cron jobs and a subagent session from the lead direct interaction that's now in a failed state with multiple error messages, along with an active main session that's been running for about 13 minutes. Looking at the active sessions now—the three cron jobs are all still running, the QLHV group monitor is active and has been running for about an hour and 47 minutes, and there's the main heartbeat monitor which is done. So comparing to the last heartbeat at 13:36 UTC, the critical sessions are stable. Looking at the session list data, I'm seeing a mix of running, done, and failed statuses across these cron jobs and Telegram sessions. There are several failed sessions from subagents spawned from the main Telegram thread, plus some zombie cron entries that appear to be stuck or outdated, and I need to flag these failed agents as requiring attention. I've identified three failed subagent sessions and one killed agent, but since these failures occurred before the last heartbeat snapshot at 13:36 UTC, they're not new changes. However, looking at the recent activity more carefully, I'm noticing something happened around 13:44 UTC when the Agent Status cron sent a report to Lead's Telegram, though this was just a notification rather than a session state change. Let me check what other sessions are currently active to get a fuller picture. So there are 36 sessions total in the list, but most are already terminated. Let me identify which ones are actually still running based on the status field—I'm seeing several with \\\"running\\\" status that need to be accounted for in the current heartbeat check. Looking at the timestamp more carefully, I'm realizing the \\\"running\\\" status on that Telegram session is actually stale—the endedAt timestamp of 1776163783190 converts to 12:03 UTC, which means it's been done for almost two hours. So the actual active sessions I need to track are just the three cron jobs and the main session, with that Telegram group session being a false positive in the list. Everything's stable across all sessions with no changes detected, so I'm staying silent on this.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"All sessions stable. Comparing against 13:36 UTC baseline:\\n\\n- ✅ `cron:ed2d0b5d` — still running (updated 13:54 UTC)\\n- ✅ `cron:6f3323ef` — still running (updated 13:51 UTC)\\n- ✅ `cron:e7885813` — still running (updated 13:45 UTC)\\n- ✅ `main` — done (since 13:06 UTC)\\n- ✅ `telegram:group:-5163901258` — done (since 13:00 UTC)\\n- ✅ Pre-existing zombies unchanged\\n\\nNo changes detected. Silent exit.\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 966,\n            \"output\": 876,\n            \"totalTokens\": 47639,\n            \"cacheRead\": 14272,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 31525,\n            \"cost\